      <p>Tarragindi sits in Brisbane's inner south, bounded to the west by Toohey Forest and adjacent to Holland Park West, Moorooka and Salisbury. It is a predominantly post-war residential suburb with a mix of original brick and timber homes and a growing number that have been renovated or substantially rebuilt. The suburb does not have the brand recognition of its inner-south neighbours, but it shares their school catchments and city access and has been repricing as buyers who find Holland Park and Greenslopes beyond reach look one step further south along the corridor.</p>

      <p>The Toohey Forest boundary is the suburb's most distinctive feature and a genuine asset for sellers on the western fringe. Homes that back onto or adjoin the forest offer an outlook and a sense of space that is difficult to replicate in most suburban settings, and these properties attract a specific buyer who values that connection strongly. For the rest of the suburb, the value story is more about comparative positioning: what can you get in Tarragindi versus Holland Park West or Moorooka at a similar price?</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Who is buying in Tarragindi</h2>
      <p>Families are the primary buyer, drawn by the school catchments and the suburb's quiet, low-traffic streets. Buyers who have been searching in Holland Park West and Moorooka and have found those markets moving faster than they can act are increasingly arriving in Tarragindi as a natural next step. First home buyers and upsizing couples are active at the entry end of the market. The investor segment is smaller than in some neighbouring suburbs, reflecting the owner-occupier character of the suburb and the premium that family buyers place on securing a home in a quiet, established street.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">What drives value in Tarragindi</h2>
      <p>Forest proximity is the most distinctive premium in Tarragindi. Homes on the western boundary that adjoin or overlook Toohey Forest consistently command prices above the suburb median and attract buyers who specifically seek that outlook. For homes elsewhere in the suburb, land size, north-facing orientation and the quality of outdoor space are the primary drivers. The condition of the kitchen and bathrooms is the internal factor that buyers most consistently reference in their post-inspection feedback, and it is the variable that most reliably separates competitive offers from hesitant ones. A well-presented home in good structural condition will always outperform a similar home with visible deferred maintenance, regardless of street or position.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Preparing for sale</h2>
      <p>Tarragindi buyers are practical and conduct thorough inspections. Pre-sale preparation should prioritise addressing any deferred maintenance and presenting the home as clean and well maintained. Fresh paint, clean flooring and a tidy garden are the baseline. For homes with original kitchens or bathrooms, even modest cosmetic updates can shift buyer perception significantly: new handles, updated tapware and fresh grout change the feel of a dated room without requiring a full renovation budget. The goal is to present a home that the buyer can move into without immediately planning how to spend money on it.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Campaign approach</h2>
      <p>Tarragindi has sufficient buyer depth to support auction for family homes on well-positioned blocks, particularly those with forest proximity or strong land content. Private treaty is the more reliable approach for homes at the lower end of the range or those where the buyer profile is more specific. The most important element of any Tarragindi campaign is the price: buyers are comparing directly against Holland Park West, Moorooka and Annerley, and they will identify a price that is out of step with those comparables. A correctly priced property in Tarragindi will generate genuine activity quickly, because the value-focused buyer who has been tracking this corridor is alert and ready to act.</p>


      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Best time to sell in Tarragindi</h2>
      <p>Tarragindi is a family suburb south of Greenslopes with a loyal buyer pool and a consistent spring-dominant seasonal pattern. September to November is the primary selling window, driven by family buyers coordinating with school enrolment timelines. Tarragindi benefits from spillover demand from Greenslopes, Holland Park, and Moorooka as those suburbs' prices have risen — buyers who have been outbid in the inner ring arrive at Tarragindi having researched the area and move quickly on well-priced stock. The autumn window (March to May) also produces strong activity. The suburb's connection to the Garden City bus corridor provides a CBD access story that attracts commuter buyers outside the seasonal peaks.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">How long does it take to sell in Tarragindi</h2>
      <p>Tarragindi homes typically sell in 28 to 40 days. The suburb has a predominantly owner-occupier buyer pool that is thorough in its due diligence but committed once a decision is made. Character homes in the northern part of the suburb nearest Greenslopes move faster than those in the southern sections that are effectively in Moorooka's price band. The competition set for Tarragindi sellers includes Greenslopes, Holland Park West, and Moorooka, and correct positioning within that comparison is the primary factor in campaign speed. Well-presented family homes with functional outdoor space and good natural light are the typology that generates the most competition.</p>

